Direct Known Subclasses:
CommonGraph, WorldGraph
public abstract class Graph extends com.telenav.kivakit.core.messaging.repeaters.BaseRepeater implements com.telenav.kivakit.core.string.AsIndentedString, com.telenav.kivakit.interfaces.naming.Named
The base class for directional graphs representing a road network, composed of GraphElements. Vertexes are connected by Edges and EdgeRelations relate vertexes and edges to each other to form higher level features like turn restrictions.

Graphs support spatial indexing and implement a variety of efficient queries for graph elements as well as simple data access methods that give statistics about the elements and retrieve elements by identifier.

All Graphs implement a DataSpecification, which determines which attributes are supported by graph elements. The data specification for a graph is one part of its Metadata, which also specifies the data version, build, supplier, format, spatial precision, size and bounds, as well as statistical information like the number of graph elements of different types.

Graphs are abstracted from their underlying store of vertex and edge data, making different implementations possible, for example mock graphs for testing purposes.

CommonGraph is the base graph implementation used by data specifications. Its CommonGraphStore holds graph data in memory in a compressed form to reduce storage requirements. It also permits fast saving and loading of GraphArchives, which are a Kryo-serialized zip file of graph element attributes. More general reading of graphs can be achieved using different subclasses of BaseGraphLoader.

For details on flyweight pattern and how it is used to make graphs efficient, refer to GraphElement.

The basic properties of graphs include various kinds of metadata and attribute support:

PropertyMap

  • name() - The name of the graph, normally derived from the resource filename
  • archive() - The archive that this graph was loaded from, if any
  • resource() - The resource that this graph was loaded from, if any
  • metadata() - Metadata describing the content and origin of the graph
  • dataSpecification() - The DataSpecification for data in the graph
  • bounds() - The bounding rectangle that encloses all graph elements
  • precision() - The Precision of graph data, and in particular polygon data
  • estimatedMemorySize() - An estimate of the size of the graph in memory
  • supports(Attribute) - True if the graph supports the given Attribute
  • supportedEdgeAttributes() - The list of all Edge attributes in the graph
  • supportedPlaceAttributes() - The list of all Place attributes in the graph
  • supportedRelationAttributes() - The list of all EdgeRelation attributes in the graph
  • supportedVertexAttributes() - The list of all Vertex attributes in the graph
  • supportsFullPbfNodeInformation() - True if the graph contains information for map enhancement
  • isEmpty() - True if the graph has no graph elements
  • isOsm() - True if the graph meets the OsmDataSpecification

Graphs can be loaded and saved to GraphArchives with load(GraphArchive) and save(GraphArchive). For a turn-key way to load graphs, see SmartGraphLoader. This loader can identify and load data stored in all the supported data formats.

The methods that load data with GraphLoader objects are used to load data from some DataSupplier in a DataFormat under a DataSpecification. GraphLoaders should be of limited use to end-users, but are a useful extension point to import data from new sources.

Graphs support a few kinds of "side-files", which are a kind of second data source. Side files can be used to add information like free flow speeds and patterns, trace counts and turns restrictions to a graph at build time.

Loading and Saving

  • load(GraphArchive) - Loads from a .graph file. A better way is to use SmartGraphLoader
  • loadFreeFlow(Resource) - Loads free flow information from the given side-file
  • loadSpeedPattern(Resource) - Loads speed pattern information from the given side-file
  • loadTurnRestrictions(Resource) - Loads turn restrictions from the given side-file
  • loadAll() - Forces all graph attributes to load into memory
  • loadAll(AttributeSet attributes) - Loads the specified attributes into memory
  • loadAllExcept(AttributeSet attributes) - Loads all attributes except those given into memory
  • load(GraphLoader) - Loads graph data from some data source
  • load(GraphLoader, GraphConstraints) - Loads graph data that meets the given constraints
  • save(GraphArchive) - Saves this graph to the given archive
  • archive() - The archive that this graph was loaded from, if any
  • resource() - The resource that this graph was loaded from, if any
  • unload() - Unloads the graph's attributes from memory
  • isUnloaded() - True if ALL graph attributes are unloaded

Although there are a number of different graph loaders, the easiest to use is the SmartGraphLoader, because it can identify and load graphs from all supported formats.

Graph Loaders

  • SmartGraphLoader - An easy way to load any kind of supported graph resource
  • DecimatingGraphLoader - Simplifies a graph
  • CopyingGraphLoader - Copies one graph to another
  • OsmPbfGraphLoader - Loads and processes data from the OpenStreetMap community
  • ContinentLoader - Loads data only from a particular Continent
  • CountryLoader - Loads data only from a particular Country
  • StateLoader - Loads data only from a particular State
  • MetropolitanAreaLoader - Loads data from a particular MetropolitanArea

Graph Creation

  • createCompatible() - Creates a graph that is compatible with the metadata from this one
  • createCompatible(Metadata) - Creates a graph compatible with the given metadata
  • createCompatible(String) - Creates a compatible graph with the given name
  • createCompatible(File) - Creates a graph using the metadata in the given file
  • createConstrained(Matcher) - Creates a graph constrained to data that matches the given matcher
  • createConstrained(GraphConstraints) - Creates a graph matching the given GraphConstraints
  • createDecimated(Distance, Angle, ProgressReporter) - Creates a graph that has been simplified

Graph objects are Repeaters that broadcast relevant messages to Listeners during operations such as saving and loading graphs. Graphs support the equals(Object) / hashCode() contract, but only by comparing metadata. Deeper comparison is available through differencesFrom(Graph, Rectangle, Maximum). Debug information is available through AsIndentedString.asString(), which is also implemented by graph elements.

      public final Graph createDecimated(Distance minimumLength, Angle maximumDeviation, com.telenav.kivakit.core.progress.ProgressReporter reporter)
      Decimates this graph. Decimation is used to reduce the data present when viewing a graph from a low level of zooming (from far out). The more zoomed out you are, the fewer details are visible, so processing required to render the data can be reduced.
      Parameters:
      minimumLength - The desired minimum length of edges to be included in the decimated graph
      maximumDeviation - The maximum amount of turning the edges can make before being decimated
      Returns:
      This graph, decimated

    • supportsFullPbfNodeInformation

      public boolean supportsFullPbfNodeInformation()
      Returns:
      True if this graph contains all PBF node identifier information (both node identifiers and node tags). Normally this information is not available in a graph, but in the case of graph editing by the OpenTerra team, it is necessary for graphs to contain all information in the PBF source file or the data cannot be uploaded to the OSM community. In general this information is voluminous and so it is stored on disk, and it is generally a good idea not to make large graphs with this level of detail.
